Parliament does not support the amendment that gives Tymoshenko freedom
Today, the Parliament of Ukraine, in the course of amendments to the Criminal Procedure Code, rejected an attempt to cancel the article according to which the leader of the opposition, Yulia Tymoshenko, was convicted.
The amendment, which would have led to the release of the former prime minister in prison, was rejected during the second reading of the bill on commuting sentences for economic offences.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was deemed unprofitable.
The sentence is not yet final; the court will consider Tymoshenko’s appeal in December.
Tymoshenko argues that the verdict is a political revenge of the regime; in the West, the process is also suspected of bias.
The proposal to repeal Article 365 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, according to which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was supported by 147 Members of Parliament.
It would require 226 votes to ratify.
