Ambassador to the EU Viceneva:
The Czechs have a reputation as ill-wishers and skeptics of the euro.
“The Lisbon Treaty has caused considerable dissension between the various organizations.”
“I didn’t expect there to be such a brutal war.”
“It will take five or six years before the situation stabilizes, calms down and all players get used to their new roles,” EU Ambassador Milena Vicenova began her lecture at the Faculty of Law.
She proved how much she adheres to her motto "Clear and open about Europe" in the first part of her lecture, where she described the individual EU institutions and the relationship between them so simple and understandable that many lecturers from the Faculty of Law of KU would be envious.
Moreover, Vicenova praised the work of the new permanent President of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
“At first, critics said he was an ordinary gray office mouse that couldn’t perform any role; I have to say, everyone was amazed at how well he did with his role.”
He is a person who can listen to the 27 participating countries at the same time, communicate with them well and who has a clear idea of which direction the EU should develop.
She explained her new position as a representative for international relations and security as an answer to the question: "Who is the European Union? What number do I need to call?"; i.e. as an important step towards unification and greater transparency of the Union's policy towards countries such as China or India.
No one is going to ban our cheeses.
Vicenova further focused on the programme, which is key for the EU in the past, present and the near future.
She called the Czech Presidency successful last year.
The Czechs were dealing with the impending financial crisis; they overcame this crisis and organized an Eastern Partnership summit.
She said that the resignation of the government at the time was a negative phenomenon that caused considerable damage to the Czech Republic.
Currently, the Czech Republic’s representatives in the EU are very busy.
As the ambassador said, both the presidency and the subsequent financial crisis caused the ongoing fermentation.
In addition, it is necessary to adopt a new seven-year EU budget, which is very difficult, given the current crisis.
Whether the budget will be scarce and economical, which areas will be preferred; which countries will receive more support and which will receive less; all these issues are in the forthcoming programme.
The Ambassador recalled the key slogans that she brought to Brussels: “About Europe, Intelligible Language”.
“I really don’t like abbreviations, foreign words and jargon that nobody understands.
How can citizens understand that in Brussels people are not trying to sell curves or round cucumbers, bananas of different sizes, or that someone is going to ban our cheeses?
It also intends to make more effective use of the EU environment and attract more Czechs to European organizations.
Multi-speed Europe – Our Future
The ambassador claims that the Czechs are considered Eurosceptics; as well as people who point out the negative rather than the positive aspects of things.
She wants more representatives of the Czech Republic to be involved in European organizations.
She believes that several factors are to blame: for example, the modesty of our candidates and their inability to write motivational letters; at the same time, with little support from the Czech side.
Along with the successful chairmanship of the Czech Republic, she noted the power and cooperation of the Visegrad Group.
"Believe me that when I meet someone from Poland and Hungary, and a Slovak joins us, the Frenchman next to me says, 'Hey, why is the assembly again the Visegrad Group?' and he is not happy about it at all.'
In the future, the Viceneva Union expects mainly new strict rules for the budgetary policy of the member states.
Compared to the new European Federation, she considers the idea of a two-speed, if not multi-speed Europe more realistic.
“We have countries both inside and outside the Eurozone.”
“We have a Schengen area and we already have an institution of enhanced cooperation.”
“For the first time, it has been said that countries that want must unite, while those that don’t want can stay away.”
"The number of such institutions will grow; it will be a truly two-speed Europe," Vicenova expects.
In this regard, she stressed the role of both the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in advancing the rule that all EU-wide issues should be discussed by all member states, not just eurozone members.
Brand history:
The innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence.
If someone wants to find the word that best expresses the IMB strategy, the closest ones are likely to be “long-lasting.”
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered very modern, although it was founded more than a hundred years ago.
The longevity of the company was laid by its first boss, the dreamer Thomas J. Watson Sr..
He believed in his motto that many of the world’s problems could be easily solved if people wanted to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the stamp around which the life of the future giant unfolded (as well as the name of his internal magazine, which IMB began to publish in 1935).
Moreover, it was the basis of the corporate culture that Watson carefully built.
“For us at IBM, long-term thinking means constantly moving towards the future.
IBM survived and thrived for a hundred years because it remained true to its original values, although it was not afraid to change everything around it.
In our first hundred years, this has allowed us to transform technology, business and company.
We hope to achieve even more in the second hundred years,” says Samuel J. Palmizano, the current CEO of the company, on the occasion of the anniversary.
Complicated system
In the 1930s, Watson approached the issue of employee care in the same way as Father in the Czech Republic – IMB employees were among the first American employees with paid leave, employer insurance, elegant uniforms and a complex system of bonuses for the best inventors and entrepreneurs.
