IBM History: From Cheese Knife to Space Flight.
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago. Its original name "Computing, Tabulation, Recording Corporation" was quite complicated.
It took the name IBM in 1924. Originally it was the name of the brand used for the company's branches in Canada and South America.
The foundations of the future IBM were laid by the merger of four companies, the history of which begins in the 1880s.
They owned technologies such as the legendary "table clock", i.e. the clock that fixes the time when employees come and go from work.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlet Flint, who until 1930 also headed the board of trustees of the company.
Flint hired Thomas J. Watson, the director of a rival company, to help him run the company.
Then the CEO pushed the founder of IBM into the shadows - Watson's ideas remain the basis of an unshakable corporate culture and individuality.
Watson headed the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name implies, started with the production and sale of various equipment for business - from cheese knives and meat cutters to cash registers.
In the first four years of Watson’s leadership, revenue doubled to $9 million, and the company began a large-scale expansion to all continents.
Watson became so important to the company that almost forty years later, his son, Thomas Watson Jr., took his place in the director's chair.
Under his leadership, IBM began to develop artificial intelligence technologies and created the first programming language.
In the 1960s, both IBM staff and computers helped NASA control spaceflights – to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 – man’s flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM line System/360.
The classic PC, which defined the computer standards of the time, called IBM 5150, appeared on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold computer manufacturing to the Chinese company Lenovo, simultaneously buying the consulting department of PricewaterhouseCoopers, thus fully concentrating on consulting and services with high added value.
Over the past three years, IBM has made great strides with its Smarter Planet concept.
Its aim is to use technology wisely in areas where this has not yet been planned and to improve the road situation and urban governance.
In commerce, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform, which helps businessmen control the entire trading cycle.
IBM’s traditions are strong even in our country.
In the former Czechoslovakia, as the first country simultaneously located in Central and Eastern Europe, IBM established its branch in 1932.
Today, IBM CZ also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
Central and Eastern Europe is headquartered in Prague, where a world-class speech recognition research team also works.
