The dynamics of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five state-owned travel agencies could operate in the former Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
As travel to the West was severely restricted, travel agencies at the time mostly sold tours to socialist bloc countries.
Thus, on vacation, Czech tourists went to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia. Then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which entailed significant restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual trips to the socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to go on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, an invitation letter from that country was necessary; otherwise an individual trip was impossible.
At the time, travel agencies offered travel to the West, but it was necessary to either stand in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or have “good friends” at the agency.
And that wasn't all.
Currency permit was required for travel to the West. It was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without a currency permit it was impossible to obtain money (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
Most often, the Czechs spent their holidays at home, which led to the emergence of a large number of cottages and summer houses, this habit continues to this day.
After 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic, thus, experienced a real revolution.
While until 1989 vacations in the GDR or Bulgaria were the culmination of our travels, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are no longer aware of is that, until 1989, we could not freely visit Croatia, currently the most popular, as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
In the early 1990s, the need to obtain a visa to the neighboring countries of Western Europe was abolished. This marked the beginning of a huge wave of short trips mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of their trips to the West. Everyone wanted to go there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents, as their income at the time was not enough for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring their own food (canned, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech krona. After decades, our tourists can finally freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income grew, which around 1997 led to another important circumstance.
Since 1997, increased demand has allowed travel agencies to prepare regular flights operated by charter airlines. Compared to the past, flights have now become incredibly cheap due to the ability to book wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs did not need a visa to visit almost all the developed world countries except the United States. This made our travels even easier.
The next significant event in the history of travel after the revolution occurred in 2000. The great demand led to the historically first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to the exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights take Czech tourists to warm exotic countries. This winter, flights from the Czech Republic will depart to twelve exotic destinations.
Currently, about 100 thousand Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished the need to obtain a visa for Czech tourists. Our country thus forever joined the most developed world countries.
For the first time in history in 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history they spent more than 15,000 kroner per person for vacation abroad, including their expenses at their destination.
