Ingeborg Winsowski
Architectural history with ups, downs and a happy end. The Austrian pavilion for the 1958 World Exhibition in Brussels won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, was empty and was abandoned.
It is now being reopened as an exhibition centre.
The Austrian pavilion, designed by Carl Schwantzer for the 1958 World's Fair in Brussels, is a famous example of modern post-war architecture with its simple forms, glass halls, bold that expressed faith in technological progress.
The Schwanzer Pavilion won the Grand Prix of Architecture in 1958 for its lightweight floating construction of steel and glass.
The building is considered a milestone in modern architecture.
This made the architect so famous that he also built the pavilion of Austria at the next World Exhibition.
In the end, he became famous around the world in 1973 for his legendary four-cylinder BMW tower and her sister - a bowl-shaped building.
The pavilion, conceived as a temporary exhibition building, was moved to the Swiss Garden near Vienna's South Station, converted and opened as a 20th-century museum in 1962 - and is often referred to as the "Twentieth-Century House" for this reason.
However, the building was not suitable for the museum for technical and spatial reasons - it did not have walls on which to hang works of art, and poor air conditioning.
However, it continued to be used until modern art in Vienna received a new home.
The house had been empty since 2001, and his condition was getting worse and worse.
Architect Adolf Krischanitz has so far restored the pavilion, which has been dubbed the "21st Century House" and will be used as a museum of contemporary art.
This museum is a branch of the Belvedere Museum, which will open its first exhibition on Tuesday evening - in all senses a joyful event.
Agnes Husslein-Arko, who became the new director of the Austrian Belvedere Gallery in 2007, contributed to the new venture.
Husslein-Arco, a graduate of the Faculty of Art History with a brilliant career as a figure skater in her youth, who worked at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and eventually became the founder and director of the Museum of Modernity in Salzburg, convinced politicians and custodians to continue the reconstruction, attracted public funds and private donations, and made a decision about how to
The new museum was to accommodate the permanent exhibition of the Fritz Wotruba Foundation, a cafe and a bookstore along with modern art. An office building was also to be built.
Strict control & limited budget
Krishanitz was then the ideal candidate for the project.
He was known, of course, for the restoration and expansion of the Vienna Secession by Josef Olbrich, and won the competition, but he also studied with Schwanzer at the Vienna University of Technology, and the pavilion was an "extremely important place" for him, where he attended exhibitions "almost every week".
He knew the original design and knew the tasks that stood in front of the building, a building that had already lost some of its grandeur and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and transformed.
The problems that arose during the last reconstruction were much more serious. The building was an "energy absorber", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles on the glass facade were replaced, a fiberglass-reinforced safety glass was inserted, and the glass roof was replaced by a high-strength safety glass.
The steel beams of the thermal bridge were reinforced or replaced, and asbestos was removed from the ceilings.
The two lower floors created a space for new use of the building, a fallen light well between the building and the street provides lighting - a practically new building, but still an elegant Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors were preserved, and the building was painted in the old red-brown color of corrosion protection.
The cinema hall is the same as it used to be.
All this under strict control of the museum management and with a limited budget.
“We often had to find material that was good, cheap, and would have been approved by the museum department,” Krischanitz says, pointing to the uneven flooring in the basement.
The building remained flexible and light despite constraints, challenges and transformations.
Krischanitz recently remarked that the pavilion "from Brussels" was rough - a typical story of "drops in the city".
Such architecture is “always out of place” and yet wants to “stimulate real awareness.”
