Two of the three largest Swiss banks merged into one large group in June 1998.
A bank was formed that was already too big for little Switzerland at the time of the merger – and a bank that continued to grow.
This was helped by the fact that the two banks that formed UBS complemented each other. One was a rich but high-level bank specializing in asset management in Zurich; the other was not so rich, but much more internationalized.
Internationalized investment bankers suddenly gained access to a large amount of money that they could use to spin the omnipotent wheel.
Two names are associated with the growth of UBS: Peter Wulffley, Executive Director of UBS Group from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, Chairman of the Board of Directors.
