Authorized management consultants, however, pointed to a weak spot. By the parameter, which in banking terminology is called "permanent income", UBS was far behind the largest banks.
UBS had failures in U.S. mortgage products.
To close the hole, UBS embarked on an adventure that nearly cost him his life.
Striving for growth, the bank itself and the hedge fund it founded invested in U.S. substandard securities.
This evolved into a large mechanism that combined securities based on U.S. mortgages and sold them further – continuing to bear the risks itself.
