The problem of birds, however, has not yet been solved.
At the first symposium on crows, in the city of Ler in East Friesland, experts argued that it was no longer possible to expel the crows from the cities.
Experts from all over Germany discussed possible solutions.
Searching for Alternatives in Cities
Conservatives argued that the root of the problem in cities was the migration of specially protected turf, indicating that the use of chemicals in agriculture was increasingly destroying traditional habitats.
Hunting, expanding construction and the felling of traditional nesting trees made life difficult for birds.
The crows are under guard.
