Peter Englund’s intense and very good new book, Beauty and Sorrow: A Personal History of the First World War, begins with a long list of actors from which the heart freezes.
Here’s a tip on how to read further: Carefully cut out this page and use it as a bookmark.
You will get to know these people very closely as Mr. Englund’s story unfolds, and this list of actors will be your GPS, your beacon at times when, like one of these men and women, you will get out of the way and get lost in the fog of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he wrote now is unusual, he describes it, quite accurately, as “working on anti-history.”
It has few known names, important treaties, or famous battles; there are almost no ambassadors, agile journalists, or discussions of tactics and military equipment.
It's not so much a book about what was, it's a book about what it was like, it's about "feelings, impressions, experiences, and the state of mind."
The book "Beauty and Sorrow" weaved together the experience of the war years of 20 more or less unremarkable men and women, on both sides of the front line, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and servants.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Someone gets captured, loses a hand or a leg, goes crazy or dies.
Their lives flicker here like church candles: new ones are added to many others, and some are extinguished at this time.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard of historical books.
This is also an amendment to the notion that the First World War was only a severe trench war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and sorrow" skilfully gives a panorama of other theaters of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
