Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Study You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just an ordinary guy expressing his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to the July massacre in Norway that killed 77 people, appeared at his first open court hearing.
Although Breivik could act alone, he was far from alone online: he spent a lot of time preparing to attack at his computer, communicating with the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, the researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
It's easy, you just have to go to Facebook.
“We realized that getting to them is not difficult at all,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European cyber populism at the UK’s DEMOS Research Centre.
The stock of personal data on Facebook is so large, Bartlett says, that researchers could easily use the site’s advertising tool to highlight the necessary demographic with scientific accuracy – something marketers have been doing for several years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million right-wing fans across Europe and then pushed them to advertise, but instead of showing them a new group or diet product, the ad asked the user to go through a survey that asked questions about their level of education, attitude to violence, and optimism about their own future.
With the help of Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 participants of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - even without leaving the office.
“It’s a whole new way to do research,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not as striking: right-wing online advocates are mostly young males dissatisfied with immigration.
But unexpectedly, “those who combine their online activity with offline activity are smarter, more democratic and less aggressive than those who just hide behind a monitor.”
DEMOS’ work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers, and political scientists use the site to explore everything from health issues to social trends that are expressed in ‘Likes’, wall posts, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three posts per day, Facebook’s “super-update” information sparks a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with a site title in the headline by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it provides an opportunity to study people who cannot be approached on the street with a notebook.
“Earlier, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them.”
“You would have to join the party and they would never accept you,” Bartlett says.
“Facebook excludes all of this – you’re addressing them directly.”
Others say that with the help of this site it would be possible to identify and investigate social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their drunken exploits on Facebook were significantly more at risk of alcoholism than students who remained silent about it.
Moreno suggests that students’ peers, such as their dorm mentors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who updates drunken statuses too often.
“You can’t solve a problem without identifying it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute.
"We found a way to identify children at risk who would not otherwise have been detected."
Facebook is also constantly extracting various kinds of data about its users.
The site’s data processing team processed statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, midterm voter turnout in 2010, as well as the National Happiness Index (mainly using information that only they have access to – champions of cyber freedom have long insisted that the site should make its extensive data collection publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become participants in a study they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strict rules for conducting offline research, online data is publicly available.
“I don’t think many users have even thought that a researcher might be watching their profiles,” says Neil Selvin, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a study he conducted in 2006 using public student pages on Facebook.
“As far as they could imagine, it was only between them and their friends.”
