7 Lessons from Steve Jobs’ Lost Interview Shown at the Theater This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing the technical genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans might consider to be the biggest discovery in a newly discovered interview, recalled ahead of previews in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood in business processes and production technologies.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer, and considered himself a hippie, but he was also the meticulous organizer and modernizer of the production process, who believed that many business executives suffered from the "disease of thinking that a really great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] a great idea separates a huge amount of skillful work from a great product."
Back in 1995, Bob Kringle created the TV series Triumph of the Nerds about the appearance of a personal computer, and he spent more than an hour with Jobs for a unique long conversation.
By that time, it had been about 10 years since Jobs was kicked out of Apple, and he was already working full-time at his new computer company NeXT in anticipation of mass Internet development.
While a small portion of Kringle's interview was used in the Nerds, he says the originals of the interview were lost during transport.
It was only after Jobs’ death that a complete VHS copy was found in the director’s garage.
This filmed material, slightly edited, became the basis for the 68-minute Steve Jobs film: The Lost Interview, which comes out at Landmark Theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for his hatred of detailed interviews, Jobs here seems unusually prepared to lay out his technological philosophy and business strategy.
And incredibly thoughtful.
At four different points during the interview, there are large intervals between questions and answers—reflections of 10-15 seconds, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to say more accurately.
There are also moments where Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems irritated by Kringle’s questions, forcing him to move faster on to issues or phenomena of greater importance.
In a pre-Pixar, iPod and iPhone Lost interview, there’s something ominously prophetic when Jobs evaluates what he sees different companies doing right and wrong and offers his own vision for the future of information technology.
It’s one thing to read about posthumous appraisals of Jobs’ work, but there’s something vulnerable and inspiring about Jobs that we see here, an alarming dreamer on the threshold of greatness.
He has a vision of what things could and should be.
Shortly after he said everything here, he went and did it.
A brief summary of the seven significant findings of the Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"All the time in business, I kept asking, 'Why are you doing this?' And the answers you always get are, 'Oh, that's just how it's done.'
No one knows why they do what they do, no one thinks very deeply in business.
Here's what I learned.
Jobs continues to describe in detail his attempts to rationalize reporting in Apple.
Disturbed by the way in which expenses were recorded, often beginning with “standard expenses” that were taken from the ceiling and then adapted using “clarification”, he created an automated structure that ensured that they could track business expenses down to the smallest detail.
The Joke on the Pope:
Jobs details the “blue box” he crafted with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
Much has been written about the device before, but the euphoria of Jobs here when describing the blue box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He tells how he and Wozniak tested the box using a phone-automatic, ordering a conversation and then connecting from one AT&T network to another until they connected as many stations as possible.
“We covered the globe half a dozen times, and you were yelling at the phone machine, and it penetrated a minute later into the neighboring phone machine,” Jobs says with a smile.
“We were young, and all we learned was that we could engineer something that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us knew a little bit, but we could have mastered a little thing that could control a big thing — it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple could ever have appeared without it.
Jobs continues to describe in detail one famous ploy he and Wozniak practically coped with by calling the Vatican through a blue box at midnight and asking the Pope to his phone, struggling to copy Henry Kissinger.
When various members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with an American diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the Pope himself was picked up to answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and Bill Hewlett's cold nickname):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to assemble the frequency meter, he found Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a summer job at Hewlett Packard.
“It had a strong impact on me, it was the only company I saw at that age, and it shaped my view of what a company is and how well they treat their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees visiting the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the very first desktop computer.”
It was the size of a suitcase, it had a small monitor with an electron beam tube, and I fell in love with it.
I used to go to HP as a teenager and go around that car and write programs for it.
About Improvised Innovation:
In several interviews, Jobs talks about the invention of new products on the fly.
At the dawn of his career, when he went to sell a handful of boards, one buyer asked him to assemble a whole computer.
Working only 30 days on credit, he had to think through the assembly and delivery of ready-made devices.
Later at Apple, he recalls the difficulties he faced when developing a computer mouse:
“I remember the furious controversies ... they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to collect a mouse that would cost $300], and I was fed up, and I went out, and I found a designer.”
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we were able to collect for $15, which was incredibly reliable.
For companies that are losing energy:
Long before he led Apple’s renaissance, Jobs accurately predicted how many industry leaders would err in their vision of the situation and lose control of their market share.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make the best copier or printer, and what?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company does not become more successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [these are the types of people] who eventually come to the management of companies, and the people who make the product are supplanted from the platform of decision makers.
The product genius that led to this monopolistic position is being supplanted by people who have no idea of the difference between good and bad products—required skill.
This is what happened to Xerox.
Xerox could capture the entire information technology industry.
It could have been ten times bigger, it could have been Microsoft in the '90s.
They were defeated by victory.
Innovation as an art form:
“A great idea is separated from a great product by a great amount of skillful work... when you unleash a great idea, it changes and grows.”
You will learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are trade-offs you need to make – some things you can’t force to make electrons, glass, robots or factories.
You need to keep 5,000 ideas in your head — these concepts — by bringing them all together.
Ultimately, it all boils down to taste – it all boils down to trying to express yourself in the best that people have ever produced, and later – trying to bring it into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have always been ashamed to steal great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh famous was that the people who worked on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happened to become the best specialists in the field of information technology in the world.
If it weren’t for information technology, they would have done amazing things in other areas.
