How to catch a lie
A quick look at the latest headlines shows how serious and ubiquitous lies and deception are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Kane is engaged in challenging allegations of sexual harassment by several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
The University of Pennsylvania administration was charged with perjury because they allegedly concealed the fact that a retired football coach raped boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught saying to U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York congressman and internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by denying his pranks, which was quickly refuted by indisputable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards was charged with financial fraud during a campaign to cover up extramarital ties.
And again, none of those who lived at the time will ever forget a media circus with President Bill Clinton caught lying about their sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in office.
Stories of cheating on exams at school and college are commonplace.
There have been cases where teachers have given students answers to tests in order to have a good assessment of the results of their activities.
Teachers who have to teach the opposite send a message that lies and fraud are acceptable.
How many lies do we face?
Within a day, research shows, you can be lied to 10 to 200 times.
Now it is assumed that a significant part of this is a lie in salvation.
Another study found that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of getting to know each other.
Identifying a lie or accusing a lie is a necessary skill for both personal and professional purposes.
Unlike a room game similar to, say, a charade where you need to shout “Catched!”, the detection of lies is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities engaged in comprehensive research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One result of the study is that most of the old myths about lies have been debunked.
Liars look in the eyes.
They don’t always get stuck, stutter, blush, or fuss.
It is not necessary to conclude from this that liars are difficult to notice and difficult to expose.
An experienced whistleblower can get to the truth by observing the structure of statements, facial expressions, question structure, and temporal characteristics.
I've spent several years researching scientific discoveries in a vast and ever-growing segment of lying knowledge, and it's clear that identifying lies is a modern skill that's easy to learn and that helps navigate our complex world -- especially if your professional responsibilities include recruiting, interviewing, negotiating, or managing.
Good liars are excellent at reading others, making them feel relaxed, managing their own emotions, and intuitively sensing how others perceive them.
We know from the study that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men lie more about themselves, while women lie more about others, usually to protect someone’s feelings that married people lie less to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are most often brazen).
We also know that if you are perceived as a fraud, others will feel less guilty about cheating you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your object.
This is called the "determination of the initial state".
This helps to provide a starting point for assessing the changes further.
Watch the pose, laughter, voice characteristics of your object.
It would be good for you to know if a person is constantly knocking with his feet in a normal state, then you will not bring unfair charges when you see the knocking with his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for groups of deceptive verbal and nonverbal actions.
Treat these groups as red flags, not proof of deception.
Deceivers can fix the upper part of their body when they try to remember their story, they can put their feet towards the door, lean towards the exit, change their posture in a certain way, or demonstrate “relief after an interview”—this exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture when all the difficult questions are behind.
Investigators often falsify the end-of-interrogation signal to simply look at this relief after the interview.
So, pay attention to the speech of your object.
Scott Peterson is known to have stumbled and exploited the past, claiming that his murdered wife was alive, leading to her searching across the country.
Distancing people can also use distancing in speech: “I didn’t have a sexual relationship with this woman...Miss Lewinsky” or repeat the difficult question completely.
The most typical verbal indicators are barely detectable.
Someone may use "qualifying language" when answering a difficult question: "Well ... to tell you the truth ... as far as I know ... as far as I know."
This makes the answer more emotional than factual, and is often a red flag.
There is no magical means to detect lies, but you can master the skill of detecting deception.
These skills will increase everyone’s chances of not becoming a victim of skilled scammers in their professional and personal lives.
