This tour marks 20 years of career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve done?
Yes, absolutely.
First, I don’t think any of us could ever have imagined that we would be in a rock band and that we’ve been doing this for more than 20 years makes it a dream.
We are very happy with our luck and we are very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and we all love making music.
We are happy to travel to places in the world where we have always wanted to go.
Everything is going very well for us.
What does it mean for you to be a significant part of the flowering grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of great collectives.
We are good friends with the guys from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It’s great when a movement grows out of a group of friends, and that’s unusual.
From time to time, one group from the same city appears, but it is much more strange when five or ten groups appear at the same time in the same city.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
I still play with some of them from time to time.
“Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden during their tour, so we’re happy to be friends with all of them and it’s an honor for us to be part of the sound of Seattle that came out.
It is also very strange that a group like yours stays together and in the same composition for so long.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than many bands exist.
First, I think we’re lucky we’re still alive, and second, we care about others.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to this, musical paths have also been opened, which give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other’s music, and it couldn’t have been better.
Your attitude to the word fame was not easy; but thanks to your success you were able to do whatever you wanted.
How do you find balance?
As we grew up, it became easier to find balance.
We take care not to be too long on tour because it’s easy to get into this game of big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are here for music, it reminds you that you have to respect music and what made it, not deciding to be famous and be a rock star, something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project, Manother Love Bone?
I think we write really good songs and at first it was great.
We have been a band for almost three years and have not released a single album, until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
There were a lot of disappointments because it lasted so long, and the most important thing is that we are still close friends with Bruce (Ferveser) and Greg (Gilmore) who started with us in the group, and when I hear a lot of song or see a photo, I think about the incredible man who was Andy, and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work.
He was a wonderful man and we miss him.
The local band Las Robertas will be responsible for opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you're familiar with her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose her to be discovered?
Yes, the producers have sent us some video offerings, and it was the band that we liked the most, so we’re looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas has to offer live, and it has to be very exciting.
Why do you keep changing words in Yellow Ledbetter at concerts?
It's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he uses the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
There's so many of them.
Among the first to come to mind, Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramon, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski ...
There are so many of them that I can talk all day about the bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam succeed in maintaining the relevance of grunge despite the fact that it is no longer in vogue?
I think we all feel a bit disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and everyone that came along at the same time, and if that’s important now, I think it’s great because it’s music worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney make music better than ever.
At first, your music was darker, but now it has become more positive.
How do you explain this change?
This is interesting because I think there are a few songs on the album that may seem easier, but there are songs like The End or Just Breathe that are considered very gloomy, although they may sound a bit positive.
From both of them, when Ed played them, I cried when I listened to them, these songs are very dark.
I think that when you grow up and you’ve had some kind of trauma in your life and you’ve lost a family member or friend, these events start to affect your creativity and your music, and these two songs, of course, reflect that for me.
So, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make dark music.
