MSS Announces Obesity Gene Search Program
Social Protection Leads Study to Find Obesity Gene in Children and Young People, Supported by IPN Experts
The Mexican Institute of Social Protection (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect the obesity gene in children and young people, called the “Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescents” protocol, which will provide a count of signs associated with overweight.
In a statement, Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, head of the Biochemistry Research Unit of the National Medical Center of the 21st Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, dietitians and social workers had been assembled.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students of the National Institute of Health of the Nation (NIPH) and the Center for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
In the study, the population (whether prescribed or not) is invited to participate by going to the MSSI sports centers participating in the study, to the Valley of Mexico City, where tests will be conducted with children each Saturday, at 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began to be conducted at the sports center in Cuautemoque (in the west of Mexico state), and from October 8, the events are held at the sports center in Nessaualcoyotl (east of Mexico state).
Once the goal of attracting 500 to 600 children has been achieved, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Center (South of Mexico City) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (North of Mexico City).
He explained that the purpose of this study is to understand the components and importance of genetics in relation to the development of obesity and to establish a risk factor among children and young Mexicans to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14 and the main goal is to gather 3,000 children and adolescents between the ages of 6 and 14 with their parents’ permission and under their supervision to fill out individual nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturday, anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, height and waist circumference), blood pressure and glucose, fat, cholesterol and insulin levels, and genetic analysis (to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity) will be carried out.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez said the study reflects the concerns of health professionals about worrying weight gain among children.
Medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006 indicate that in just 6 years there was an increase: in the case of boys, 77 percent were obese, in the case of girls, 47 percent; in the case of overweight, there was also a significant increase," said the expert of MSSI.
He said that the validity of the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican is 65 percent descendant of American Indians, 30 percent descendant of Europeans, and five percent descendant of Africans, and this condition affected genes that are associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that basically the consequence of obesity genetics is the body’s inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and it is stored as fat.
The researcher explained that the immediate benefit for the participants is a comprehensive assessment of the children, which can reveal whether they have at least some degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds on the neck (acutes) and forearms means the likelihood of metabolic disorders and even prediabetes.
The information is treated with complete confidentiality, doctors hand it over in writing to parents, to whom they explain all the measurements and lifestyle changes that need to be taken to avoid the disease.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez explained that there are three main reasons provoking overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of the TV and using transport over short distances instead of walking.
This is also due to the high calorie intake, that is, the increased consumption of sweet drinks and carbohydrates (tamala, bread, pizza, burgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetic predisposition analyzed in this program.
Asphalt UNAM can avoid cracks
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, has developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a blend of the best quality, resistant to environmental and temperature influences.
If the signals sent by the road surface were given attention, it would be necessary to repair about 200 thousand pits for each rainy season in the metropolitan area in the Valley of Mexico City, says Rafael Herrera Nahera, a researcher at the UNAM School of Chemistry, and adds that if the process of construction and maintenance of the paved road surface is correct, then the number of pits can be reduced.
In his lecture Technological View of Pits, read as part of the International Year of Chemistry, it is reported that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture with characteristics close to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen can be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and therefore counteract pit formation.
He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some of which are of high molecular weight, called asphalts, and others of low molecular weight, called maltens, which together give the road surface its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of bitumen lies in the fact that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it retains an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures bitumen becomes brittle, he said.
This means that the resistance of street asphalt is not constant, but changes throughout the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, said a specialist in the field of chemical engineering.
The chemtrail scientist noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with a flexible coating, which is made up of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the top layers is bitumen, composed of small stones, lowered into bitumen and then compressed.
Every stone that makes up this coating, he said, is immersed in bitumen.
When driving vehicles and exerting effort, it helps the forces to distribute very well on the road surface.
If it were modified asphalt, they would be even better distributed, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt coating, he added, placed the last layer, which is called the wear layer, which is made of fine stone, in fact sand also immersed in asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will come into contact with the wheels of transport, it should have more resistance than asphalt coating and provide road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and distribute these efforts, the wear layer also requires proper thickness, and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the state of asphalt.
When the earth is raw, the water penetrates the coating and it is difficult to get out of it, this causes the softening of all layers of the coating and, therefore, the formation of pits.
