Medicalization or not, but 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, according to experts appointed by the Royal Society of Canada.
And 68.6% of them end up dying in the hospital.
The highest rate by country is in Quebec, where 86% of deaths occur in a hospital.
On the delicate issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to a conclusion that contradicts the position of the federal government, which has already stated that it does not want to change anything in the criminal code regarding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Now, according to experts who have also studied the position of all countries where such actions have been legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalization entails abuse in use, that is, euthanasia or suicide with outside help against people who cannot or do not want to make such a decision.
On the contrary, Jocelyn Downey, who presented the report, confirmed during a teleconference that the majority of such cases were in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide were not legalized.
Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal.
Suicide with outside help is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal, explains Jocelyn Downey.
Canadians in favor of euthanasia
It should be remembered that 85% of Canadians are in favor of euthanasia because, according to a 2010 survey by Angus Reid, they believe that it will allow people to ease their suffering at the end of life.
And 66% believe that the legalization of euthanasia will not signal that the life of the elderly or the disabled is of less value.
As for people who assisted with suicide, 41% of respondents believe that they should not be prosecuted.
As for the extension or termination of medical care for the patient, the situation is less unambiguous, say the authors of the report.
They also propose, among other recommendations, that the Penal Code should establish that legal termination of medical care is not a crime.
The Committee of Experts also requires health professionals to be trained in a spirit of respect for the rejection of end-of-life medical care without fear of prosecution.
With regard to palliative care, the committee urges the government, health care institutions and physicians to work together to develop the best palliative care possible, and not only in cancer cases.
Finally, with regard to palliative or terminal sedation, already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee demands that it be applied when it does not serve to dull physical pain like euthanasia and is subject to the same restrictions.
Comments from other experts
Some experts in the field of health-related legislation have already commented on the conclusion of the report of experts of the Royal Society of Canada.
Pierre Deschant, a health law specialist, described the position of the experts who signed the report as “extreme” because, among other things, it does not limit the use of euthanasia to deaths.
This opens the door to a situation where anyone who is tired of life and who is over 18 years old can ask for help in committing suicide, says Meter Deshan, who discussed the summary of the report yesterday.
Desham also stressed that the authors of the report seem to place the independence of the individual above all other values that make up the social fabric of society.
He said, “There are warning signs and prohibitions in society.”
Health law specialist Margaret Somerville also expresses “categorical disagreement with the findings of the report, which she called a “euthanasia manifesto.”
Margaret Somerville, herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, contests, in particular, the report’s data on abuse in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, as in the Netherlands and Oregon.
