Austria-Hungary
The introduction of the "golden rule" of the budget into the Constitution
The leadership of a large coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to write the budget "golden rule" in the constitution to reduce the budget deficit and thus avoid possible downgrades by the rating agencies of Austria's state credit rating (triple A).
Chancellor Werner Faymann personally announced the decision at the end of a meeting of the Council of Ministers, with Austrian public debt at 74.6%, which is significantly higher than the upper threshold of the norm of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty, but below the public debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
If Austria’s solvency had fallen by only one point, from AAA to AA+, we would have had to pay interest of three thousand million euros more each year, the vice chancellor and foreign minister from the Christian Democrats Michael Spindelegger argued.
Thus, Austria is fulfilling the requirement of the Eurozone summit in Brussels on 26 October; Heads of State and Government have demanded a reduction in budget deficits by the end of 2012 and a return to balanced public accounts through a constitution or equivalent law.
The decree, adopted by the Austrian government, resembles the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to adopt this "rule".
Until 2017, the structural deficit of the state budget should be reduced by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, and from 2017 the structural deficit of the state budget of a federal state in any year should not exceed 0.35% of GDP, and land, like communes, should represent balanced budgets.
The goal is to force public debt to fall below the 60% mark enshrined in the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/2021.
