Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogmas.
If there is a topic that cannot be decided after a brief discussion or under the influence of emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is a healthy trend that election meetings become an occasion to reflect on the fate and place of nuclear power.
The dispute will not bear fruit until all the economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options have been explored.
France must base its opinion on objective facts and rational data.
Now we are 7,000 million people on the planet, demographic development will entail a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge part of the world’s population is deprived of vital elements.
During the same period, it will be necessary to make up for the growing shortage of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity continuously, without forgetting the critical need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate imbalances – a topic that has disappeared from the environmental debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these factors.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to abandon nuclear energy.
This is not the case for Belgium, which makes its decision dependent on the need to find a source capable of replacing nuclear energy, or Switzerland, which intends to build only the most modern reactors.
On the other hand, the UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil are just a few of those who are determined to continue their projects.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add one installation to its kit, resuming the construction of the station, which was interrupted after the accident on Three Mile Island.
Although the model of Germany based on renewable energy is sometimes cited as an example, reality contradicts this argument.
The choice of Berlin will result in an increase in the cost of electricity, increased energy dependence, exacerbated by an increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, a jump in carbon dioxide emissions due to the construction of gas and coal stations.
In a few months, all these unpleasant effects will already be noticeable.
Consider the example of Denmark.
The European turbine champion, from whom it receives 30% of its electricity, is also the biggest consumer of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; causing carbon dioxide emissions and electricity prices to be 65% and 50% higher, respectively, than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbors pay 40% more for electricity than French households.
Since in a globalized economy the price of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and the guarantee of maintenance of industrial equipment in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in nuclear energy will lead to a large increase in the cost of electricity, which will make illusory beautiful statements about the new industrialization of our country and the protection of purchasing power.
The price that most French refuse to pay, especially because they do not object to this type of energy in principle.
It should be remembered that the country’s energy policy has made it possible to create an industry of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Strongly export-oriented, it attracts a plethora of international trade-focused small and medium-sized enterprises and creates many jobs that cannot be relocated to another industry.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would have to sacrifice a large number of these enterprises and lose 6,000 million euros a year from French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrical engineer would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years if its manufacturer were to be shut down?
To solve the energy equation, one must recognize that there are no divine or diabolical sources of energy production.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear energy, maintaining the highest level of security is undoubtedly a vital issue.
In France, we have a security body that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing energy centers, such as Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is universally recognized, are full of the same obsession with security.
Over the course of 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions, but without any consequences for humans or the environment.
In Chernobyl, a reactor device and an unforgivable human error led to a tragedy.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident occurred as a result of two natural disasters of unprecedented force that resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
The fruit of this step and the cooperation between the security authorities, operators and French and German designers, EPR, represents a project to counteract such phenomena.
As it is considered by all energy professionals looking to build the reactor, stopping its construction in Flamanville will be a great gift to Areva and EDF competitors, clearing the way for them to gain leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best combination of energy sources for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogmas and biased maneuvers to prevail in a dispute that is so important to the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or a good for the economy?
Nicolas Sarkozy’s immigration policy has been criticized from various sides – overloading of police, judicial and administrative services, subordinate to the policy of figures and the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France as a “human rights state”.
Then there was the administrative oppression of foreign students, which got into the news when the Minister of Internal Affairs (Liberaci<0xC3><0xB3>n, 23 May) said that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and waiters".
But it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The right and the left agree on this point.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac, who in 1976 stated that “900,000 unemployed would not be a problem in a country with 2 million foreign workers” and on the left by Michel Rocard, who explained in 1990 that France “cannot accept the poor from all over the world”.
The only difference is the level of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of invading the territory of the Polish Hordes of Plumbers was felt by both left and right.
Both sides see immigration as a burden for the French economy and for French society.
The difference is only in the level of generosity they will allow to show to immigrants.
In his program, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande confined himself to banality, saying that “joint work will solve our immigration problem.”
This notion of immigration as a burden and a problem can give an electoral advantage, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Jeffrey Cameron remind us in a recent book summarizing the latest data on immigration (Special People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Determine Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Publishing House, 352), there is a broad consensus among specialists about the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment.
Restricting immigration leads to weakening growth and lowering employment.
Fears of immigrant influence are based on the notion that they are able to replace local workers, especially low-skilled ones, provoking wage cuts.
But experience shows that in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than they are replacing the local workforce by doing jobs that lack the local workforce.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local labor, and the most qualified - in dynamic sectors where training is not related to job offers.
Positive impact on wages
Just as it would be difficult for a surgeon to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, the complementarity between locals and immigrants leads to the fact that the arrival of immigrants has a positive effect on the wages of local workers.
Giovanni Perry estimated that a 1% increase in migratory flows leads to a 0.6-0.9% increase in real long-term wages.
And this is without taking into account the fact that the diversity introduced by immigrants contributes to the creation of new ideas and economic growth (among the American Nobel laureates there is a large proportion of naturalized immigrants, and Google, Intel, Paypal and Yahoo - all were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also bring net profit to social security systems, giving an average of 1% of the total budgets of European countries.
According to the World Labour Organization, for example, in Germany, an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will bring a net profit (income minus expenses) of an average of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>150,000 to the state budget during his life.
Nicolas Sarkozy at the beginning of his mandate was going to “teeth” to cling to the missing points of growth.
The teeth mentioned, which were used to scare away immigrants, gave the exact opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, it remains to understand European democracy
Democracy is a valuable acquisition; but at the same time fragile.
The European continent must remember that, having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, in the 20th century it survived the tragedies of World War I, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the Gulag, as well as Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and colonels in Greece.
Some believed that in order for democracy to finally triumph over its enemies, it was enough to arrange a vote and make it as direct as possible.
Since the time of Napoleon the "Small" it is known that it comes from the superficiality of thinking.
A universal vote, while a prerequisite for democracy, is not a sufficient condition and may even become a “tool of suppression,” as the Republican philosopher Etienne Washreau once said.
No, democracy requires much more - public space, public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of authorities, education, education, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The European crisis we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is primarily a political crisis and a crisis of democracy.
In this regard, the palinody of the truth-lie Greek referendum will have a double exposing effect, demonstrating both the need for a serious policy change and the unpleasant feeling of its impossibility and inconsistency.
This duality needs to be understood in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front line of the struggle for democracy has now shifted and, in the opinion of many, Republican soldiers are now aiming in the wrong direction.
We will not win anything by demanding a series of national referendums, organised as necessary and in a chaotic manner.
"Carte blanche" for the absolute European monarch or jump with his feet tied into the abyss of nationalism - what a choice for a citizen!
No, we do not dream of a guillotine blade, but of a joint, clear and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at the pan-European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal, and it is not known how many of them will have to be listed, because there is only one crisis - the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe is completely subject to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, suffering from its weakness and lack of solidarity.
The whole of Europe is completely humiliated on the international stage.
Many are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but all of Europe is gradually losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
It is necessary to urgently return the management of the European project to popular sovereignty.
Because only by working together will Europeans be able to reduce everyone’s debt burden, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing in it.
A way out of the crisis will require solutions at the pan-European level, and they cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy without leading us to disaster.
After a long discussion of this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now demanding a European economic government.
Let it be.
But to imagine it without the stronger economic, political and democratic integration that has come to life is another madness and a new impasse.
We need to start a new phase of European construction.
To establish a republic in France, it was necessary to “create” republicans.
A revolution of interests would not suffice.
This lesson remains in force.
We must build a Europe that is united on an economic level.
This can only be done by creating a more democratic Europe at the political level, a genuine people’s European sovereignty.
To create Europe, let us create Europeans.
