Terrorist Front Spreads from Sahara to Nigeria
Paris is concerned about ties between the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The long-established links between the al-Qaeda terrorist group in the Muslim Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian Boko Haram sect have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even said that Algerians are now convinced of this.
“The way these two organizations are using and the intelligence reports show that they are actively cooperating,” he explained, without going into details.
Paris seems to have come to similar conclusions.
An investigation into the abduction of two French men in Niger in January revealed two links.
Kidnapped in a restaurant in Niamey by people close to Aqmi, Antoine de Leocourt and Vincent Delori were apparently killed the next day along with several of the kidnappers during an operation carried out by French special forces.
Among the debris left over from the operation, French and Nigerian investigators found several phone sim cards belonging to the terrorists.
The Axis of Terror
An analysis of the calls made indicated several interlocutors in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), investigators are particularly interested in two numbers; one points to a Nigerian who has long lived in Maidiguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a person allegedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
“This is a step forward, but we certainly need to wait for more reliable evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
“It has been known for many years that the sect is receiving financial and ideological support from outside and that it is becoming more and more active,” said Kunle Amuvo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, this support has become increasingly apparent from Boko Haram’s actions and statements and her methods, which now include the use of suicide bombers and increasingly sophisticated explosive devices of the same type that Aqmi uses.
The international community, led by Washington, is now pressing Abuja to pay attention to the problems that Boko Haram is creating.
The fact is that the Nigerian authorities have traditionally regarded this group as a community of enlightened people of no interest.
Fast success
Founded in 2002 in Maidiguri at the mosque, school and under the imam-fundamentalist Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram—which means “Western education is sin”—promotes the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the organization has achieved rapid success.
It is politicized and requires strict adherence to the Sharia, and its activists have begun to fight against the ungodly central government.
It focuses mainly on churches, bars and authorities.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists showed special activity, committing numerous attacks on police departments.
Abuja’s reaction, as usual, is uncompromising.
The army blocked the city and left behind 800 dead.
Muhammad Yusuf, taken alive, was killed in prison.
Now the sect is radicalizing and will go beyond its northern legions.
Last Christmas, she claimed responsibility for the action that killed 80 people in Jos, and then another one in Abuja.
In Abuja in June, Boko Haram staged the first suicide attack on a fortified police headquarters.
In August, the local representation of the United Nations will be their first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which is coming from Mauritania through Nigeria to Somalia, is now a concern for all security experts.
Today, with Aqmi fortified in Mali and Niger and al-Shabaab Somalis operating in Kenya, Boko Haram poses a new threat to the continent.
Last week, during a conversation with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned of the dangers of Boko Haram and expressed readiness to share all available information.
