The North Stream, a new gateway for Russian gas to enter Europe.
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Western Europe and Russia directly at the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has been launched.
It is designed to supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian giant gas producer, wanted to celebrate this event with a pump.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the Baltic coast, between the orchestra’s performance and exquisite snacks, in the opening of the Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany under water.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mart Rutte jointly turned the symbolic valve that controls the flow of Russian gas into the Western European network.
According to the new gas pipeline, 27.5 million additional cubic meters of gas will be supplied to Western Europe every year by the first pipeline with a length of 1,224 km, connecting the Leningrad region with the land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline should be ready by the end of 2012, providing a total of 55,000 million cubic meters of gas equivalent to the total consumption of France.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already being discussed.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met fierce resistance from Poland and the Baltic states.
The Nord Stream will indeed allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose some of their power: they will find it harder to influence Russia by threatening to shut down access to Western European markets.
At the most tense moment of the debate, Warsaw did not stop at comparing the Nord Stream with the new German-Soviet Pact, hinting at an alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is striving for greater security of its supplies.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to achieve its understanding of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries, which consume large volumes of gas and whose own reserves are already running out.
“This pipeline is part of the cooperation with Russia, it is a new artery that organically connects us,” Fillon said, opening the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent large gas contracts are important both politically and economically.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the heads of Gazprom, who were present in large numbers in Lubmin, the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel enclosed in concrete to protect it from ship anchors.
It lies at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, it was necessary to bypass the minefields left over from the Second World War.
“A hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to take many steps to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metal snake weighing 242 Eiffel towers, without breaks along its entire length, without valves and without service stations.
The control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but the project managers refused it because Sweden was not happy that the Russian state-owned company would settle permanently on its shores.
“In the event of an accident, we will shut down the flow of gas in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline will go into the air.
But this seems unlikely to the designers who designed the seams, designed to leak only once every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the condition of the gas pipeline will be carried out by an underwater robot that pulls the ship for external observation, as well as by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
The cigar-shaped device is introduced into the pipeline with a diameter of 1 meter and pushed forward by a flow of gas.
Upon arrival after 3 full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters per second, it gives accurate information about any deformation of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without the need for the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is carried out only at the expense of its pressure.
It is 200 bar on departure and 100 bar on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), Dutch Gasunie and French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which was tasked with building and operating the pipeline.
Its headquarters are in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Then Gazprom leased this company for twenty years with the possibility of extending the entire volume of gas transportation.
“Gazprom will pay for the full volume, regardless of how much gas will actually be transported,” says Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the gas pipeline was provided by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of works will be 7.4 million euros for two pipelines.
GDF Suez’s investment will be around $240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will recoup their costs, because Gazprom takes all the risks.
The pipeline exits from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy shore planted with coniferous trees.
Valves 4.5 meters high form the output terminal of the gas.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before pumping it into German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full capacity it will be 3 million per hour, and in 2012 6 million.
Moleskine Brand Notebook
Moleskine, created by an Italian company fifteen years ago, will bring back the taste of the letter.
It has the scent of adventure, hours spent behind a letter in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable by the rectangular black cover, by the rubber band, by the yellowish-white pages, as if yellowed with time.
However, the Moleskine notebook, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
Italian company Modo Modo, located in Milan, decided to launch designer notebooks.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant to the company, took responsibility for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique, moleskin - a lacquered cotton fabric used, for example, to cover benches.
It is claimed that this type of notebooks are highly valued by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine brought into line with today’s taste an old and forgotten thing that was iconic for avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” said Maria Sebregondi, who has since become a management brand at Modo Modo.
Success has come.
From 2006 to 2010, sales increased by 25% and reached 12.7 million units.
We have come a long way from the production of the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were produced.
Moleskine has crossed the borders of Italy and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
Setting the profile of a typical buyer is difficult because a notebook equally attracts a businessman, a student and a person of a free profession.
Moleskine buyers are cosmopolitan, broad-minded and educated.
The small Italian company, which initially had only 12 employees, now has 100 and two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its notebooks in Fnac bookstores, shops in the centers of small cities and was able to gain wide fame.
“We followed the spirit of the time and this new need to write despite the advent of email,” Maria Sebregondi explains.
This distinctive cultural trait accompanies the development of Moleskine; the brand recently organized the "Roundabout Way" exhibition, where architects and artists demonstrated their own notebooks.
In August, he also launched covers with a leopard pattern on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products, which now include handbags, pens, computer bags. The brand includes all kinds of support.
A success that gave rise to envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which has written a new page in Moleskine’s history.
Why is the unemployment rate among disabled workers so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th week of employment for people with disabilities begins today.
Despite a public charity policy launched in 2005, the rate of unemployment among disabled people is still double the average, 19% vs. 9% for the general population.
Disappointing?
“No,” said Eric Blanche, CEO of Adapt, the organization that organizes the Disabled Persons Employment Week.
“There has been a lot of progress in 15 years.”
"At that time, the proportion of unemployed was not 2 but 3 times higher."
“But there is still a lot of work to be done.”
I must say that for a disabled person there are still many obstacles to employment.
Among them, there are more elderly: 37% over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a rather low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree, and out of 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is very common, which is 85% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to return to work and that make up the essence of the problem,” said Christian Grapen, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about a mentality that is changing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre Association commissioned by Cité found that the managers surveyed had low levels of disability knowledge and “presented themselves with solid people in wheelchairs or mentally or mentally disabled.”
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the target of having 6% of workers with disabilities set out in a law passed in 1987.
The last known figures for 2008 are 2.6%.
“Today we are about 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organization responsible for collecting taxes from companies that do not comply with the law.
Proof: The number of "taxable" organizations, as well as the amounts paid, decreased from 59,000 to 46,000 organizations in 2007-2011 (and from 606 million to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law that raised the tax put a lot of pressure on companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects an increase in consciousness, particularly in large enterprises.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of organizations with employees ranging from 20 to 49 have employees with disabilities, compared to 82% of organizations with employees ranging from 100 to 199.
